gan has 16 electoral votes in the Electoral College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archives.gov/federal-register/electoral-college/allocation.html|title=Distribution of Electoral Votes|website=[[National Archives and Records Administration]]|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMichigan is expected to be tightly contested in 2020, as it was the closest state by margin in the [[2016 United States presidential election in Michigan|2016 election]], where President Trump became the first Republican to carry Michigan\u2019s electoral votes since [[1988 United States presidential election in Michigan|1988]], when [[George H. W. Bush]] won in a national landslide against [[Michael Dukakis]].\n\n==Primary elections==\nThe primary elections were on March 10, 2020.\n\n===Republican primary===\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Michigan Republican primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Michigan Republican primary|Results}}}}\n\n===Democratic primary===\n[[Bernie Sanders]] and former [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]] were the two major declared Democratic candidates.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=Elizabeth Warren Formally Announces 2020 Presidential Bid in Lawrence, Mass. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-2020.html |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=The New York Times |date=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Michigan Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Michigan Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n==General election==\n===Predictions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Source\n!Ranking\n!As of\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[The Cook Political Report]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cookpolitical.com/sites/default/files/2020-03/EC%20030920.4.pdf|title=2020 POTUS Race ratings|website=The Cook Political Report|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|March 9, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Stuart Rothenberg|Inside 