t/epic-mra/press/Stwd_Survey_Jan2020_Media_Freq.pdf EPIC-MRA/Detroit Free Press][https://eu.freep.com/story/news/politics/elections/2020/01/15/mike-bloomberg-other-democrats-lead-donald-trump-michigan-poll/4469175002/]\n|Jan 9-12, 2020\n|600 (LV)\n|\u00b1 4%\n|34%\n|{{party shading/Other}}|'''44%'''{{efn|Listed as \"Would vote to replace Trump\"}}\n|22%{{efn|19% listed as \"would consider voting for someone other than Trump\"; 3% as \"undecided/refused\"}}\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[https://ssl2002.webhosting.comcast.net/epic-mra/press/Stwd_Survey_Mar2019_Media_Freq.pdf EPIC-MRA/Detroit Free Press]\n|Mar 3-7, 2019\n|600 (LV)\n|\u00b1 4%\n|31%\n|{{party shading/Other}}|'''49%'''{{efn|\"Vote to replace Trump\" with 49%}}\n|20%{{efn|\"Consider voting for someone else\" with 16%; \"Don't know/refused\" with 4%}}\n|}\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2020 United States presidential election]]\n* [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]]\n* [[2020 Republican Party presidential primaries]]\n* [[2020 United States elections]]\n\n==Notes==\n;Partisan clients\n{{notelist-ua}}\n;Voter samples and additional candidates\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{United States elections, 2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States presidential election by state|Michigan]]\n[[Category:United States presidential elections in Michigan|2020]]\n[[Category:2020 Michigan elections|Presidential]]\n", "name_user": "PutItOnAMap", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_United_States_presidential_election_in_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Joseph Kesselring", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}}\n\n\n\n''[[Arsenic and Old Lace (play)|Arsenic and Old Lace]]'' appeared at a time of strong isolationist sentiment regarding European affairs, of the sort that was very strong at where Kesselring sent to college. The play suggested that the elite running America had a murderous heritage.<ref>{{cite book|author=Matthew C. Gunter|title=The Capra Touch: A Study of the Director's Hollywood Classics and War Documentaries, 1934-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XLD--w2GHrkC&pg=PA45|year=2012|publisher=McFarland|pages=49\u201351}}</ref>  Kesselring lived in a college house that would later be the basis of the set of ''Arsenic and Old Lace'', and locals have tried to identify who were some of the character models he used.  Kesselring was an Episcopalian who did not fit in well with the strait-laced college. He dropped out of college in 1924.<ref>See [http://mennonitelife.bethelks.edu/2013/05/another-look-joseph-kesselring-bethel-college-and-the-origins-of-arsenic-and-old-lace/  Keith L. Sprunger, \"Another Look Another Look: Joseph Kesselring, Bethel College, and the Origins of ''Arsenic and Old Lace'', ''Menonnite Life'' (May, 2013).] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224134601/http://mennonitelife.bethelks.edu/2013/05/another-look-joseph-kesselring-bethel-college-and-the-origins-of-arsenic-and-old-lace/ |date=February 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nKesselring died on November 5, 1967, in [[Kingston, New York]], at the age of 65.\n\nIn 1980, the [[National Arts Club]] created the Joseph Kesselring Prize for up-and-coming playwrights. It was funded by Kesselring's [[widow]], Charlotte. Among the playwrights who have won the prize are [[Tony Kushner]], [[David Adjmi]], [[Doug Wright]], [[Anna Deavere Smith]], [[David Auburn]], [[Rajiv Joseph]], [[Melissa James Gibson]], [[Jo Carson]], [[Nicky Silver]], [[David Lindsay-Abaire]], [[Jos\u00e9 Rivera (playwright)|Jos\u00e9 Rivera]], [[Naomi Wallace]], [[Philip Kan Gotanda]], [[Kira Obolensky]], [[Tracey Scott Wilson]], and [[Marion McClinton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118000155.html?categoryid=15&cs=1&query=rajiv+kesselring |title=Kesselring Fellowship honors duo; Playwrights Rajiv Joseph, David Adjmi awarded |publisher=Variety |date=2009-02-13 |first=Gordon|last=Cox|accessdate=2010-04-03}}</ref><ref>[http://x-sites.exchangenyc.org/content/projectsthe-kesselring-fellowship The Kesselring Fellowship] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106115232/http://x-sites.exchangenyc.org/content/projectsthe-kesselring-fellowship |date=January 6, 2010 }}, The National Arts Club, The Exchange website. Retrieved February 19, 2010.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://archives.nypl.org/the/22616 Joseph O. Kesselring writings, 1932-1970], held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kesselring, Otto}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:People from Kingston, New York]]\njoseph kesselring was and amazing playwright \n\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Opposition to World War II]]\n[[Category:Bethel College (Kansas) faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American people of Canadian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}}\n\n'''Joseph Otto Kesselring''' (July 21, 1902 &ndash; November 5, 1967) was an American playwright who was best known for writing ''[[Arsenic and Old Lace (play)|Arsenic and Old Lace]]'', a hit on Broadway from 1939 to 1944 and in other countries as well.  He was born in New York City to Henry and Frances Kesselring. His father's parents were immigrants from Germany. His mother was an English Canadian.<ref>US Census 1920, New York Borough of Manhattan, enumeration district 913, Sheet 19A</ref>  Kesselring spent much of his life in and around the theater. In 1922, he began teaching vocal music and directed stage productions at [[Bethel College (Kansas)|Bethel College]], a [[Mennonite]] school in [[North Newton, Kansas|North Newton]], [[Kansas]]. After two years, Kesselring left teaching and returned to the stage, working for two years with an amateur theatrical group in [[Niagara, New York|Niagara]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>[http://www.methactoncommunitytheater.org/ars_res.htm Dramaturgy: Notes from the Director] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513233410/http://www.methactoncommunitytheater.org/ars_res.htm |date=May 13, 2008 }}, Methacton Community Theater website. Retrieved February 19, 2010.</ref> He began working as a freelance [[playwright]] in 1933, completing 12 original plays, of which four were produced on Broadway: ''[[There's Wisdom in Women]]'' (1935), ''Arsenic and Old Lace'' (1939), ''Four Twelves are 48'' (1951), and ''Mother of that Wisdom'' (1963).  ''Arsenic and Old Lace'' was his masterpiece. It ran for 1444 performances on Broadway and 1337 performances in London, and became a staple in high school and [[dinner theater]] circuits. [[Arsenic and Old Lace (film)|The 1944 movie adaptation]] was also a comedy hit.\n\n''[[Arsenic and Old Lace (play)|Arsenic and Old Lace]]'' appeared at a time of strong isolationist sentiment regarding European affairs, of the sort that was very strong at where Kesselring sent to college. The play suggested that the elite running America had a murderous heritage.<ref>{{cite book|author=Matthew C. Gunter|title=The Capra Touch: A Study of the Director's Hollywood Classics and War Documentaries, 1934-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XLD--w2GHrkC&pg=PA45|year=2012|publisher=McFarland|pages=49\u201351}}</ref>  Kesselring lived in a college house that would later be the basis of the set of ''Arsenic and Old Lace'', and locals have tried to identify who were some of the character models he used.  Kesselring was an Episcopalian who did not fit in well with the strait-laced college. He dropped out of college in 1924.<ref>See [http://mennonitelife.bethelks.edu/2013/05/another-look-joseph-kesselring-bethel-college-and-the-origins-of-arsenic-and-old-lace/  Keith L. Sprunger, \"Another Look Another Look: Joseph Kesselring, Bethel College, and the Origins of ''Arsenic and Old Lace'', ''Menonnite Life'' (May, 2013).] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224134601/http://mennonitelife.bethelks.edu/2013/05/another-look-joseph-kesselring-bethel-college-and-the-origins-of-arsenic-and-old-lace/ |date=February 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nKesselring died on November 5, 1967, in [[Kingston, New York]], at the age of 65.\n\nIn 1980, the [[National Arts Club]] created the Joseph Kesselring Prize for up-and-coming playwrights. It was funded by Kesselring's [[widow]], Charlotte. Among the playwrights who have won the prize are [[Tony Kushner]], [[David Adjmi]], [[Doug Wright]], [[Anna Deavere Smith]], [[David Auburn]], [[Rajiv Joseph]], [[Melissa James Gibson]], [[Jo Carson]], [[Nicky Silver]], [[David Lindsay-Abaire]], [[Jos\u00e9 Rivera (playwright)|Jos\u00e9 Rivera]], [[Naomi Wallace]], [[Philip Kan Gotanda]], [[Kira Obolensky]], [[Tracey Scott Wilson]], and [[Marion McClinton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118000155.html?categoryid=15&cs=1&query=rajiv+kesselring |title=Kesselring Fellowship honors duo; Playwrights Rajiv Joseph, David Adjmi awarded |publisher=Variety |date=2009-02-13 |first=Gordon|last=Cox|accessdate=2010-04-03}}</ref><ref>[http://x-sites.exchangenyc.org/content/projectsthe-kesselring-fellowship The Kesselring Fellowship] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106115232/http://x-sites.exchangenyc.org/content/projectsthe-kesselring-fellowship |date=January 6, 2010 }}, The National Arts Club, The Exchange website. Retrieved February 19, 2010.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://archives.nypl.org/the/22616 Joseph O. Kesselring writings, 1932-1970], held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kesselring, Otto}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:People from Kingston, New York]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Opposition to World War II]]\n[[Category:Bethel College (Kansas) faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American people of Canadian descent]]\n", "name_user": "I know this!! haha", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(joseph kesselring is amazing)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Kesselring"}
